<h2 id="motivation">Motivation</h2>

<p>I want to install Spark on my PC.</p>

<h2 id="preparation">Preparation</h2>

<p>I read chapter 2 of Oâ€™Reillyâ€™s <a href="https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/learning-spark/9781449359034/">Learning Spark</a>.</p>

<h2 id="method">Method</h2>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Download Java from <a href="https://java.com/en/download/win10.jsp">here</a> and install it to a directory with no spaces in the path, e.g., <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">C:\Java</code>.</p>

    <p>If the directory contains space, the Spark shell may fail with an error described <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/44027151/why-does-spark-shell-fail-with-was-unexpected-at-this-time">here</a>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>Create system variable <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">JAVA_HOME</code> and set it to the path in which Java is just installed.</li>
  <li>Download Spark from <a href="http://spark.apache.org/downloads.html">here</a> and unzip it to a directory with no spaces in the path, e.g., <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">C:\Spark</code>.</li>
  <li>Add the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bin</code> folder in the Spark installation to environment variables.</li>
  <li>Open <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">cmd</code> and type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">pyspark</code> to open the Python version of Spark shell or type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">spark-shell</code> to open the Scala version.</li>
</ol>

